solutions.content:
Given ```k```, ```str```, how to check ```str``` is a palindrome after ```k``` operations.
If the size of ```str``` is odd, there must have a number of  a letter is odd, and others are even.
If the size of ```str``` is even, number of each letter are even.
If the size of ```str``` is odd, ```k >=number of odd // 2``` can make ```str``` be a palindrome after ```k``` operations.
If the size of ```str``` is even, ```k >=number of odd // 2``` can make ```str``` be a palindrome after ```k``` operations.
We just focus on which letter whose number is odd or even, we can use a bit mask to do it, a bit is 1 mean a letter whose number is odd or is even.

We can use prefix sum to check which letters whose number is odd, just use ```prefix[r+1] ^ prefix[l]```, ```prefix[i]``` is a bit mask for ```s[0~i-1]``` 
and use ```bit_count``` to check number of letters whose number is odd.

tc is O(s.size() + queries.size()), sc is O(s.size() + queries.size())
### c++
``` cpp
class Solution {
public:
    vector<bool> canMakePaliQueries(string s, vector<vector<int>>& queries) {
        vector<int> prefix (s.size() + 1, 0);
		// prefix sum to check which letters whose number is odd
        for(int i = 0; i < s.size(); i+=1) 
            prefix[i+1] = prefix[i] ^ (1 << (s[i] - 'a'));
        auto bit_count = [] (int x) {
            int cnt = 0;
            while (x){
                cnt += x & 1;
                x >>= 1;
            }
            return cnt;
        };
        vector<bool> ans (queries.size());
        for (int i = 0, odd; i < queries.size(); i+=1) {
            int& l = queries[i][0], &r = queries[i][1], &k = queries[i][2];
            odd = bit_count(prefix[r+1] ^ prefix[l]); // number of letters whose number is odd
            if (k >= odd/2) ans[i] = true;
        }
        return ans; 
    }
};
```
