solutions.content:
**Solution:**

The idea is to have prefix sums of frequencies so that we can quickly answer range queries.
Similar to normal prefix sum we will be able to say what are the character frequencies of any substring.
Then just iterate over all queries and see how many frequencies are odd.
For example if odd frequency = 1, it is a palindrome ( "a", "b", "aba").
Otherwise it should be less or equal to twice the number of edits we allowed to make in the query.
That is because if, let's say number of odd frequencies = 3 and we make 1 edit we can reduce the number by 2.
For example "abc" we can change to "aba" by making just one edit.
So each edit reduces number of odd frequences by 2 and odd frequency = 1 is special because it's a palindrome, so we round it down to an even number (odd = odd & ~1)

**Code:**
```
typedef array<int, 26> A26;    
A26 operator-(const A26& a, const A26& b) {
    A26 answer{};
    for(int i = 0; i < 26; i++) {
        answer[i] = a[i] - b[i];
    }
    return answer;
}
class Solution {    
public:
    vector<bool> canMakePaliQueries(string s, vector<vector<int>>& queries) {
        int n = s.size();
        vector<A26> prefs;
        A26 curr{};
        prefs.emplace_back();
        for(char c : s) {
            curr[c - 'a']++;
            prefs.push_back(curr);
        }        
        vector<bool> answer;
        for(const vector<int>& q : queries) {
            A26 freq = prefs[q[1]+1] - prefs[q[0]];
            int odd = 0;
            for(int i = 0; i < 26; i++) {
                if(freq[i] > 0 && freq[i] % 2 != 0) {
                    odd++;
                }
            }
            odd = odd & ~1;
            answer.push_back(odd <= q[2]*2);
        }
        return answer;
    }
};
```

