For people who gets TLEs or does not get why other posts' solutions work, hope this short explanation can help. 

##### How to generate all submasks of a given mask? 

Given a bitmask *m* of a puzzle string, to find all its submasks, simply do:

```
int sub = m;
while (sub > 0) {
	sub = (sub - 1) & m;
}
```

For why does this work please follow this link of an awesome explanation: 
https://cp-algorithms.com/algebra/all-submasks.html

##### Why do we do this?

One of the brute force ways of checking which word is valid might be looping through the entire collection like this:

```

    public List<Integer> findNumOfValidWords(String[] words, String[] puzzles) {
        Map<Integer, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
        List<Integer> lst = new ArrayList<>();
        for (String s : words) {
            int mask = 0;
            for (char c : s.toCharArray()) {
                mask |= (1 << (c - 'a'));
            }
            map.put(mask, map.getOrDefault(mask, 0) + 1);
        }
        for (String s : puzzles) {
            int mask = 0;
            for (char c : s.toCharArray()) {
                mask |= (1 << (c - 'a'));
            } 
            int first = (1 << (s.charAt(0) - 'a'));
            int res = 0;
            for (int w : map.keySet()) { // looping through the whole map
                if (Integer.bitCount(w) > s.length()) continue;
                if ((w & first) == first) {
                    if ((w & mask) == w) {
                        res += map.get(w);
                    }
                }
            }
            lst.add(res);
        }
        return lst;
    }
```
This would get TLE for large test cases because 

*1 <= words.length <= 10^5*

which means there could be 10^5 keys in the map and the loop could run 10^5 times.

However, if we visit all submasks of a puzzle word mask mentioned above, since 

*puzzles[i].length == 7*

at worst case the loop will only run 2^7 times, which significantly reduce the runtime.

##### Lessons
1. Take advantage of the input data range to make optimizations (as hint 1 suggests).
2. Methods to generate submask of a given mask 

