When I saw the description, I knew it must be bitmap. However, I spent hours to conqure the last testcase.

Until I realized the most important point lies in the **last lines** of the **Condition** .
What I do is **just swap two expression in if** to:
```
(bitmap_p[j] & bitmap_w) == bitmap_w && ((1<<(bitmap_p[j]>>26)) | bitmap_w) == bitmap_w
```

1. How bitmap builds ?
we know words is more than puzzles, so we build bitmap map array of puzzles to *save memory*.
from **puzzles[i].length == 7**: this is a const value, so we just copy-paste 7 times `1U<<puzzles[i][0]-'a'` after `bitmap_p[i] = `.
	the last `((puzzles[i][0]-'a')<<26)`  just for *no subsequent reference* of `puzzles[i]`,  5-bit value can denote decimal number from 0 ~ 31 and 26+5 is exactly 31 bits, which fits a `int` fine!

2. why swap the two expression?
while the first one just need 3 cheap arithmetic logic operation, the second one needs 2 more shift operation.
the hit rate is not that high, the second expression compares 1 byte only, the other one compares whole string!

The solution is not as fast as I expected but it keeps simplicity and memory-saving.

