solutions.content:
This is a really plain one, once you figure out a quick and cheap way to compare strings all the time.

And we can do so by hashing them into bitmasks so that we will store a `1` into each. slot matching an alphabet letter, starting from the right and ignoring of course repeated characters. For example `"aaa"` becomes just `1` in a bitmask representation; `"acdgaacgca"` becomes `1001101` (with the `1`s representing respectively: `g00dc0a`) and so on.

Once we have done so, all the work of comparing strings becomes way cheaper!

To do so, we will first of all declare a few variables:
* `wLen` and `pLen` will store, respectively, the length of `words` and `puzzles`;
* `bits` is going to be a 2D array there we will store our hashes by letter contained (first index) and position (second index);
* `bitsPos` will tell us how much we have written in each sub-array of `bits`, with all his cells initially set to `0`;
* `s` is a convenient reference to a string we will later use (initialised with the first element of `words`, just because a reference like that has to be initialised);
* `res` will be our accumulator variables, already set on the right size (`pLen`) to avoid reallocations.

We will then initialised all the elements of `bits` to be `0` and then proceed parsing `words` with the pointer `i` going across all its elements and using also `tmp`; in this loop we will:
* assign the currently pointed element `words[i]` to `s`;
* reset `tmp` to be `0`;
* compute `tmp` going through each character `c` in `s` and:
	* subtracting `'a'` from it, in order to make each value of `c` in the more convenient `0 - 25` range;
	* using the binary OR operation to add the currently relevant bit (`1 << c`) to `tmp`;
* we will then store the final hashed bitmask in all the relevant buckets in `bits` with another loop, storing `tmp` into `j`, setting `k` to be `0` and proceeding until `j` is not `0` we will:
	* check if the rightmost bit (the currently parsed one) of `j` is `1` and, in case, store `tmp` into `bits[k][bitsPos[k]]`;
	* increase `bitsPos[k]`;
	* left shift `j` by one position;
	* increase `k` by `1` (since we are parsing increasing character values, as long as we still have some left - ie: `j != 0`).

After all this preparation is done, time to properly parse `puzzles`, similarly going through all of its element with the pointer `i` and also using the variables `tmp` and `start`, we will:
* assign the currently pointed element `words[i]` to `s`;
* reset `tmp` to be `0`;
* compute `tmp` going through each character `c` in `s` and:
	* subtracting `'a'` from it, in order to make each value of `c` in the more convenient `0 - 25` range;
	* using the binary OR operation to add the currently relevant bit (`1 << c`) to `tmp`;
* assign the normalised value of the first character of `s` to `start`;
* look with `j` through all the `bitsPos[start]` elements that contain `start` and:
	* if all the letters of `bits[start][j]` are present in `tmp` (`(bits[start][j] & tmp) == bits[start][j]`), then we increase `res[i]`.

Once done, we can just `return` `res` :)

The code:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> findNumOfValidWords(vector<string>& words, vector<string>& puzzles) {
        // support variables
        int wLen = words.size(), pLen = puzzles.size(), bits[26][wLen], bitsPos[26] = {};
        string &s = words[0];
        vector<int> res(pLen);
        // preparing the bitmask arrays
        for (int i = 0; i < 26; i++) {
            fill(bits[i], bits[i] + wLen, 0);
        }
        // parsing words into bitmasks
        for (int i = 0, tmp; i < wLen; i++) {
            s = words[i];
            // turning s into a bitmask
            tmp = 0;
            for (char c: s) {
                c -= 'a';
                tmp |= 1 << c;
            }
            // storing the bitmask in bits by its letters
            for (int j = tmp, k = 0; j; j >>= 1, k++) {
                if (j & 1) bits[k][bitsPos[k]++] = tmp;
            }
        }
        // parsing puzzles into bitmasks
        for (int i = 0, tmp, start; i < pLen; i++) {
            s = puzzles[i];
            // turning s into a bitmask
            tmp = 0;
            for (char c: s) {
                c -= 'a';
                tmp |= 1 << c;
            }
            // storing the bitmask in bits by its starting letter
            start = s[0] - 'a';
            for (int j = 0, lmtJ = bitsPos[start]; j < lmtJ; j++) {
                if ((bits[start][j] & tmp) == bits[start][j]) res[i]++;
            }
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

