solutions.content:
The question explicitly states 2 condition for a word to be valid:
For a given puzzle word, the corresponding word should:
1. Word should contain the first letter of the puzzle word
2. All the letters of the word should be contained in the puzzle word

So, the brute force approach can be, we can iterate through each puzzle word, and then for each puzzle word, we can iterate through all the words of the word array. Then check if the word contains the first letter of the puzzle word. If yes, then we can check if all the letters of the word is contained in the puzzle word, if yes then we can update the count of the number of words satisfied for a puzzle word by 1. Similarly, we check the same for the rest of the words in the word array and keep updating the count. At the end of each iteration of the puzzle word, we will add the answer in the final list.

The code for the same is as follows:
```
class Solution {
    public List<Integer> findNumOfValidWords(String[] words, String[] puzzles) {
        List<HashSet<Character>> arr_word = new ArrayList<>();
        List<HashSet<Character>> arr_puzzle = new ArrayList<>();
        List<Integer> ans = new ArrayList<>();
        for(String x : words)
        {
            HashSet<Character> hs = new HashSet<>();
            for(char c : x.toCharArray())
            {
                hs.add(c);
            }
            arr_word.add(hs);
        }
        for(String y : puzzles)
        {
            HashSet<Character> hs = new HashSet<>();
            for(char d : y.toCharArray())
            {
                hs.add(d);
            }
            arr_puzzle.add(hs);
        }
        for(int i=0;i<puzzles.length;i++)
        {
            String puzzles_word = puzzles[i];
            int count = 0;
            HashSet<Character> temp1 = arr_puzzle.get(i);
            char first = puzzles_word.charAt(0);
            outer : for(int j=0;j<words.length;j++)
            {
                HashSet<Character> temp = arr_word.get(j);
                if(!temp.contains(first))
                    continue;
                String current_word = words[j];
               inner: for(char e : current_word.toCharArray())
               {
                   if(temp1.contains(e))
                       continue;
                   else
                      continue outer;
               }
                count++;
            }
            ans.add(count);
        }
        return ans;
    }
}
```

But this method will result in Time Limit Exceeded because the number of the words in the Puzzles array is around 10^4 and in the words array is 10^5. 

So, we need to come with a better approach. For this there is a prerequisite and we need to know about concept of Bitmask. You can read this article on the link page to understand about it more clearly.

https://cp-algorithms.com/algebra/all-submasks.html

Here we can make the bitmask for all the words in the the words array and by taking them as a key, store them in a hash table, along with their count as the value. Though getting the TLE error, gives us an indication of using a bitmask. But then using a hashmap and concept of enumeration of submasks of a given bitmask is not intuitive. Then we can iterate through all the puzzle words, and enumerate all submasks for the bitmask of the puzzle word. The number of submasks which is for a given bit mask we just change the positions that are set in the bit mask which generates all the subsets of the bit mask. TWe iterate over each puzzle word. For each puzzle word, we enumerate all submasks for the bitmask of the puzzle word. This will give us a complexity of O(2^puzzle_word.length) but here it is given that puzzle_word.length = 7 at max, so it is not a problem. Then we check if if the given submask is present in the hash table, we then add the value corresponding to it to the count of valid words for the puzzle word. This way, we keep on doing the same thing for all the submasks of the puzzle word. But, there is an issue here, we also need to consider the valid words contains the first letter of the puzzle. In order to satisfy this, while creating the bitmask, we don't consider the first letter of the puzzle as it should always be set. What we do is while checking the hashtable for the submask, we do an OR opearation of submask and the bitmask for the first letter of the puzzle, and then use it as a key. This ensures that the first letter is always present in the word. 

The code for the same is as follows:

```
class Solution {
    private int bitMask(String word)
    {
        int mask = 0;
        for(char c : word.toCharArray())
        {
            mask |= 1 << (c - 'a');
        }
        return mask;
    }
    public List<Integer> findNumOfValidWords(String[] words, String[] puzzles) {
        HashMap<Integer,Integer> hm = new HashMap<>();
        for(String word : words)
        {
            int key = bitMask(word);
            hm.put(key,hm.getOrDefault(key,0)+1);
        }
        List<Integer> ans = new ArrayList<>();
        for(String puz : puzzles)
        {   
            int first = 1 << (puz.charAt(0) - 'a');
            int count = hm.getOrDefault(first,0);
            //Otherwise count will be double, once for 1, once for 0 in the submask for first letter of puzzle word 
            int mask = bitMask(puz.substring(1));
            int subset = mask;
            while(subset > 0)
            {
                count += hm.getOrDefault(first | subset, 0);
                subset = (subset - 1) & mask;
            }
            ans.add(count);
        }
        return ans;
    }
}
```

