solutions.content:
**Method 1:** Although this brute force method gets TLE, it forms the base of the further optimized solutions, so its essential to understand this trivial but important solution.
```
/**
 * 1. puzzle[0] (first letter of puzzle) is in word
 * 2. All letters of word are in puzzle.
 * 3. Length of puzzle = 7
 * 4. All letters of puzzle and word are lowercase alphabets
 * 5. puzzle has unique letters
 */
public List<Integer> findNumOfValidWords(String[] words, String[] puzzles) {

	var wordLettersList = new ArrayList<Set<Character>>();
	for (var word : words)
		wordLettersList.add(toSet(word));

	var validWordsCount = new ArrayList<Integer>();
	for (var puzzle : puzzles) {
		var puzzleLetters = toSet(puzzle);
		var count = wordLettersList.stream()
								   .filter(wordLetters -> wordLetters.contains(puzzle.charAt(0)) && 
													      puzzleLetters.containsAll(wordLetters))
								   .count();
		validWordsCount.add((int) count);
	}
	return validWordsCount;
}

/**
 * @param s string
 * @return character set of s
 */
private Set<Character> toSet(String s) {
	return IntStream.range(0, s.length())
					.mapToObj(s::charAt)
					.collect(Collectors.toCollection(HashSet::new));
}
```

**Method 2:** With our base idea clear that we need to hash and check for subsets, let's optmize it by taking advantage of the fact that the given character set is lowercase alphabets, i.e. only 26 possible characters, which will fit perfectly in a 32 bit int. If uppercase where there as well, then we'd have used long. For more characters, our approach might have been slightly different.
This approach is better than method 1, but still gets TLE because of the inner loop. It's possible that in an interview setting this method may get accepted, but for leetcode we need to optimize further.
```
public List<Integer> findNumOfValidWords(String[] words, String[] puzzles) {
	var maskFreq = getMaskFrequency(words);
	var validWordsCount = new ArrayList<Integer>();

	for (var puzzle : puzzles) {
		var puzzleBitMask = toBitMask(puzzle);
		var puzzleFirstLetter = 1 << puzzle.charAt(0) - 'a';
		var count = 0;

		for (var wordBitMask : maskFreq.keySet()) {
			var isPuzzleFirstLetterInWord = (wordBitMask & puzzleFirstLetter) == puzzleFirstLetter;
			var puzzleContainsWord = (wordBitMask & puzzleBitMask) == wordBitMask;
			if (isPuzzleFirstLetterInWord && puzzleContainsWord)
				count++;
		}
		validWordsCount.add(count);
	}

	return validWordsCount;
}

private Map<Integer, Integer> getMaskFrequency(String[] words) {
	var maskFreq = new HashMap<Integer, Integer>();
	for (var word : words)
		maskFreq.compute(toBitMask(word), (k, frequency) -> (frequency == null) ? 1 : frequency + 1);
	return maskFreq;
}

private int toBitMask(String s) {
	return IntStream.range(0, s.length())
					.map(i -> 1 << (s.charAt(i) - 'a'))
					.reduce(0, (a, b) -> a | b);
}
```

**Method 3**: Optimize inner loop. AC solution, beats 97% submissions.
```
public List<Integer> findNumOfValidWords(String[] words, String[] puzzles) {
	var maskFreq = getMaskFrequency(words);
	var valid = new ArrayList<Integer>();

	for (var puzzle : puzzles) {
		var puzzleBitMask = toBitMask(puzzle);
		var puzzleFirstLetter = 1 << (puzzle.charAt(0) - 'a');
		var count = 0;
		var combination = puzzleBitMask;

		while (combination != 0) {
			if ((combination & puzzleFirstLetter) == puzzleFirstLetter)
				count += maskFreq.getOrDefault(combination, 0);
			combination = (combination - 1) & puzzleBitMask;
		}
		valid.add(count);
	}

	return valid;
}
```

