solutions.content:
Think of puzzles as a list of queries, because we have `O(n)` queries and `O(m)` words, it is a good idea to preprocess the `words` in `O(m)` time and run query in time of proportional to `n`.

Steps:
1. Generate and count the occurrence of bit mask for each word in `words`, where bit mask is the occurrence of letters in word.
2. For each puzzle, generate a bit mask, and sum the occurrence over all its submasks that include the first letter of puzzle, as for every submask represent one of the combination of letters that a word has.

[Here](https://cp-algorithms.com/algebra/all-submasks.html) introduce a common and useful technique to iterate over all submasks.


**Complexity**

Time: `O(m + n * 2^k)`, where k is size of puzzles[i],
Memory: `O(m)`.

**Code**

```
class Solution {
public:
    int get_mask(string s) {
        int mask = 0;
        for (const auto &c : s)
            mask |= (1 << (c - 'a'));
        return mask;
    }

    vector<int> findNumOfValidWords(vector<string>& words, vector<string>& puzzles) {
        int n = puzzles.size();
        vector<int> res(n, 0);
        unordered_map<int, int> dict;

        // Counter of character set for each word
        for (const auto &w : words) {
            ++dict[get_mask(w)];
        }

        // Iterate over submasks for each word in puzzles
        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
            char first = puzzles[i][0] - 'a';
            int mask = get_mask(puzzles[i]);
            for (int m = mask; m > 0; m = --m & mask) {
                if (m & (1 << first)) // Consider a set that contains first letter
                    res[i] += dict[m];
            }
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

